==================================================
1) Tagging
==================================================
	
	Like most VCSs, Git has the ability to tag specific points in history as being important. Typically people use this functionality to mark release points (v1.0, and so on).

==================================================
2) Listing Your Tags
==================================================
	
	$ git tag
	v0.1
	v1.3

	$git tag -1 "v1.8.5"

	Listing the available tags.


==================================================
3) Creating Tags (Annotated Tags)
==================================================
	
	$ git tag -a v1.4 -m "my version 1.4"

	Annotated tags is created using the above command and you also add a messsage


==================================================
4) Creating Tags (Lightweight Tags)
==================================================


	$ git tag v1.4-1w

	Creating tags without message

==================================================
4) Tagging later
==================================================

	$ git tag -a v1.2 <commit_hash>


	Tag commits to specific tag( version number ).


==================================================
4) Sharing Tags
==================================================

	$ git push origin v1.5

	By default git doesnt push tags, to push tags to remote use the above command.


==================================================
4) Inspecting a Remote
==================================================
 
 	$ git remote show <remote>

 	To check details of the all remote pulls and push.


==================================================
4) Checkout out Tags
==================================================
	
	$ git checkout 2.0.0

	
	$ git checkout -b version2 v2.0.0

